From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Brandon Mahdavi <brandon.mahdavi@mahcom.com>
Date: Fri, 10 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: dsa: qca8k: skip host FDB entries on CPU ports,
 purge stale dynamic ones

DSA installs host FDB entries for the same {MAC, VID} once per CPU port
in use. qca8k used to overwrite the single ATU entry, so the last CPU
port won and host reachability broke for user ports served by the other
CPU port (e.g. Netgear R7800 with wan bridged into br-lan). Merging the
CPU port bits into the destination mask instead is no better: the ATU
forwards a unicast hit to every port set in the mask, so a host entry
spanning both CPU ports makes the switch deliver one copy of each
host-bound frame per CPU port. This duplicated nearly all host traffic
and halved throughput on TP-Link TGR1900, Archer C2600 and ASUS
RT-AX89X, with "failed to delete ... from fdb: -22" log spam from the
asymmetric delete path.

Host FDB entries are a pure optimization on this switch: the unknown
unicast forward mask in GLOBAL_FW_CTRL1 already contains all CPU ports
and is filtered per ingress port by PORT_LOOKUP_CTRL members, so a
host-bound frame with no ATU entry reaches exactly one CPU port, the
conduit of its ingress port, and the tag parser delivers it to the
correct user netdevice from either conduit. The conduits run in
promiscuous mode (qca8k does not implement FDB isolation), so no RX
filtering relies on these entries either.

Skip programming unicast host FDB entries on CPU ports entirely. This
fixes the multi-CPU bridged setups without ever creating a unicast
destination mask with more than one CPU port bit, regardless of how a
board assigns its conduits. (This host-FDB skip was originally authored
by Olaf Marzocchi and tested by @xback for the multi-CPU-port case.)

Relying on unknown-unicast flooding only holds while the address has
no ATU entry at all, though. When a station roams from a wired user
port to an interface behind the CPU (e.g. a wireless client moving
from another AP, or a client behind a WDS link), the ATU still holds
the dynamically-learned entry pointing at the user port the station's
traffic used to ingress. A unicast hit on that entry forwards all
host-bound frames to the stale port - where the ingress port filter
discards them as same-port traffic - and the CPU never sees them.
Hardware cannot correct the entry either: source address learning is
disabled on the CPU port (assisted learning), so the station's
post-roam traffic never re-teaches the ATU. The result is a per-MAC
blackhole: the roamed client associates and transmits fine, but every
downstream frame from the wired side is dropped in silicon until the
stale entry ages out (if ever), while the bridge believes the entry
was offloaded because the skipped add reports success.

Observed in the field on IPQ4019 (assisted learning enabled, single
CPU port): a roamed client's traffic stayed blackholed indefinitely,
with 'bridge fdb show' reporting the stale entry on the wired port:

  xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx dev lan vlan 1 self
  xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx dev phy1-ap0 vlan 1 master br-lan

Deleting the stale entry by hand restored connectivity instantly.

Purge any dynamically-learned ATU entry for {addr, vid} when the host
FDB add is skipped: the bridge just told us the address lives behind
the CPU now, so a dynamic entry on any user port is stale by
definition. The address then returns to unknown unicast flooding,
which is exactly the delivery mechanism host-bound traffic relies on
above. Static entries are left untouched, as they reflect deliberate
configuration rather than learning.

Verified on IPQ4019: the stale entry is purged at association time
and roaming recovers instantly.

Fixes: openwrt/openwrt#21317
Signed-off-by: Brandon Mahdavi <brandon.mahdavi@mahcom.com>
---
 drivers/net/dsa/qca/qca8k-common.c | 56 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 56 insertions(+)

--- a/drivers/net/dsa/qca/qca8k-common.c
+++ b/drivers/net/dsa/qca/qca8k-common.c
@@ -322,6 +322,36 @@ exit:
 	return ret;
 }
 
+static int qca8k_fdb_purge_dynamic(struct qca8k_priv *priv, const u8 *mac,
+				   u16 vid)
+{
+	struct qca8k_fdb fdb = { 0 };
+	int ret;
+
+	mutex_lock(&priv->reg_mutex);
+
+	qca8k_fdb_write(priv, vid, 0, mac, 0);
+	ret = qca8k_fdb_access(priv, QCA8K_FDB_SEARCH, -1);
+	if (ret < 0)
+		goto exit;
+
+	ret = qca8k_fdb_read(priv, &fdb);
+	if (ret < 0)
+		goto exit;
+
+	/* Nothing to purge, or a deliberately configured static entry */
+	if (!fdb.aging || fdb.aging == QCA8K_ATU_STATUS_STATIC) {
+		ret = 0;
+		goto exit;
+	}
+
+	ret = qca8k_fdb_access(priv, QCA8K_FDB_PURGE, -1);
+
+exit:
+	mutex_unlock(&priv->reg_mutex);
+	return ret;
+}
+
 static int qca8k_vlan_access(struct qca8k_priv *priv,
 			     enum qca8k_vlan_cmd cmd, u16 vid)
 {
@@ -829,6 +859,29 @@ int qca8k_port_fdb_add(struct dsa_switch
 	struct qca8k_priv *priv = ds->priv;
 	u16 port_mask = BIT(port);
 
+	/* The ATU forwards a unicast hit to every port set in the
+	 * destination mask, so a host entry spanning multiple CPU ports
+	 * would deliver one copy of each host-bound frame per CPU port.
+	 * Skip host entries entirely: unknown unicast is already forwarded
+	 * to all CPU ports by GLOBAL_FW_CTRL1 and filtered by the ingress
+	 * port LOOKUP_MEMBER, so host-bound frames reach exactly one CPU
+	 * port, the conduit of the ingress port.
+	 */
+	if (dsa_is_cpu_port(ds, port) || dsa_is_dsa_port(ds, port)) {
+		/* The bridge now sees {addr, vid} on a software port behind
+		 * the CPU (e.g. a wireless interface). A dynamically-learned
+		 * ATU entry may still point at the user port the station
+		 * roamed away from; a unicast hit on it forwards host-bound
+		 * frames to that stale port, where the ingress port filter
+		 * discards them, instead of flooding them to the CPU. Purge
+		 * such an entry so the address is unknown unicast again.
+		 */
+		if (!vid)
+			vid = QCA8K_PORT_VID_DEF;
+
+		return qca8k_fdb_purge_dynamic(priv, addr, vid);
+	}
+
 	return qca8k_port_fdb_insert(priv, addr, port_mask, vid);
 }
 
@@ -839,6 +892,9 @@ int qca8k_port_fdb_del(struct dsa_switch
 	struct qca8k_priv *priv = ds->priv;
 	u16 port_mask = BIT(port);
 
+	if (dsa_is_cpu_port(ds, port) || dsa_is_dsa_port(ds, port))
+		return 0;
+
 	if (!vid)
 		vid = QCA8K_PORT_VID_DEF;
 
